// ch05 §5.12: "Reuses real C++ lambda syntax verbatim ... including
// generic (C++14, `auto` parameter) lambdas." A generic lambda's
// `operator()` is itself a function template, monomorphized per
// call-site argument type -- the same underlying mechanism as §5.11's
// concept-constrained generic functions.
//
// NOTE: as of this test's writing, generic functions/concepts are not
// yet implemented (see 13_unsupported_robustness/
// concept_and_generic_functions_are_rejected_not_crashed.scpp) -- a
// generic lambda's `auto` parameter plausibly depends on the same
// monomorphization mechanism, so this case may only start passing once
// that lands too, not purely as a closures-specific fix.
int main() {
    return [](auto x) { return x + x; }(21);
}
